BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION

First, we need to find the missing side. By the Pythagorean Theorem, we have:

    [``
\begin{aligned}
  [$base]^{2}+[$height]^{2} &= x^{2} \\
  [$base**2]+ [$height**2] &= x^{2} \\
  [$base**2+$height**2] &= x^{2} \\
  \sqrt{[$base**2+$height**2]} &= x \\
\end{aligned}
    ``]

Next, we need to simplify the radical. To simplify [`[$hypotenuseSquared]`], first prime factor it, and then "take out" any pair of repeated factors from inside the square root:

    [``
\begin{aligned}[t]
   [$hypotenuseSquared] [$output11] \\
            [$output12] \\
            [$output13]
\end{aligned}
    ``]

The length of the hypotenuse is [`[$hypotenuse]`].

By definition:

    [`` \sin \theta = \frac{\text{opposite leg}}{\text{hypotenuse}} ``]

    [`` \cos \theta = \frac{\text{adjacent leg}}{\text{hypotenuse}} ``]

    [`` \tan \theta = \frac{\text{opposite leg}}{\text{adjacent leg}} ``]

An acronym to help you memorize those 3 definitions is: *SOH CAH TOA*.

In the given triangle, the longest side (facing the right angle) is the hypotenuse. In other words, side [`c`] is the hypotenuse, because it is opposite from right angle [`\angle C`].

For [`\angle A`], side [`a`] is the "opposite leg," because it's opposite to [`\angle A`]; this implies side [`b`] is the "adjacent leg" in terms of [`\angle A`].

For [`\angle B`], side [`b`] is the "opposite leg," because it's opposite to [`\angle B`]; this implies side [`a`] is the "adjacent leg" in terms of [`\angle B`].

By the above definitions, before we rationalize the denominators, we have:

    [`` \sin A = \frac{[$base]}{[$hypotenuse]} ``]

    [`` \sin B = \frac{[$height]}{[$hypotenuse]} ``]

    [`` \cos A = \frac{[$height]}{[$hypotenuse]} ``]

    [`` \cos B = \frac{[$base]}{[$hypotenuse]} ``]

    [`` \tan A = [$tangentOutput1]  [$ansTangentA] ``]

    [`` \tan B = [$tangentOutput2]  [$ansTangentB] ``]

The tangent values don't need to be further simplified. Next, we need to rationalize the denominator for sine and cosine ratios.

To rationalize the denominator of [`\sin A`], we calculate:

    [`` 
\begin{aligned}
   \sin A &= \frac{[$base]}{[$hypotenuse]} \\
   [$output21]
   [$output22]
   &= [$ansSineA]
\end{aligned}
    ``]

Note that the value of [`\cos B`] and [`\sin A`] are the same.

To rationalize the denominator of [`\sin B`], we calculate:

    [`` 
\begin{aligned}
   \sin B &= \frac{[$height]}{[$hypotenuse]} \\
   [$output31]
   [$output32]
   &= [$ansSineB]
\end{aligned}
    ``]

Note that the value of [`\sin B`] and [`\cos A`] are the same.

Finally, we have:

    [`` \sin A = [$ansSineA] ``]

    [`` \sin B = [$ansSineB] ``]

    [`` \cos A = [$ansCosineA] ``]

    [`` \cos B = [$ansCosineB] ``]

    [`` \tan A = [$ansTangentA] ``]

    [`` \tan B = [$ansTangentB] ``]

END_PGML_SOLUTION

